      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for modelRiskLevel 3.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical R2023 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V procedures. All simulation scripts are version-controlled in Git (tag v3.2.1). Software installation qualification records are on file. Achieved Gradation 3 — formal SQA plan with traceability to simulation outputs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions must be reproduced within 1% for linear statics.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark cases (LE1, LE10, NL1) were executed and results compared to reference solutions. Maximum deviation was 0.7%. Code verification is considered sufficient for the linear-elastic regime governing stiffness and yield force prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change <2% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "Four mesh densities were evaluated (element edge lengths 0.8, 0.5, 0.3, 0.2 mm at screw-rod interface). Richardson extrapolation yields a GCI of 1.4% for construct stiffness and 1.9% for yield force. The 0.3 mm mesh was selected for production runs, achieving Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error quantification was considered beyond the scope of the current submission cycle. The assessment team noted that iterative solver convergence tolerances and round-off accumulation in the nonlinear contact iterations were not systematically characterized. This factor was deferred to a future revision without a concrete plan or timeline, and no bounding argument was provided to demonstrate that omission is inconsequential at modelRiskLevel 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs and boundary conditions must be independently reviewed by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "All model setup files (material definitions, contact pairs, boundary condition scripts) were independently reviewed by a second FEA engineer not involved in model development. Discrepancies were resolved prior to production runs. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions must be documented and justified relative to the physics of ASTM F1717 compression-bending.",
      "rationale": "Linear-elastic isotropic material models are justified for Ti-6Al-4V at the strain levels observed prior to yield. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface is consistent with published tribological data for titanium alloy interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity is activated to capture load-deflection response at 40 mm displacement. Model form assessed at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to coupon test data or manufacturer specifications with uncertainty bounds reported.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) for Ti-6Al-4V were obtained from tensile coupon tests on material from the same lot as the test constructs (n=5 coupons, CV<3%). Screw geometry was digitized from micro-CT scans (voxel size 25 µm). Input uncertainty was propagated via Monte Carlo (1000 samples). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples must be representative of the device design and manufactured to drawing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "All 11 constructs were assembled from production-intent components manufactured to engineering drawings. Dimensional inspection confirmed compliance with tolerances. Samples were split across two independent laboratories (n=6 and n=5) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must replicate the boundary conditions imposed in the FEA model.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single displacement rate (25 mm/min) under ambient conditions. No variation in test configuration (e.g., load application angle, fixture compliance) was explored. This limits confidence in the generalizability of the validation evidence and results in Gradation 1, below the required level of 2. This known shortfall is documented and accepted by the sponsor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters must be mapped directly to experimentally measured quantities with documented traceability.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA (fixed inferior block, displacement-controlled superior block) directly replicate the F1717 fixture configuration. Torque preload on set screws was measured during assembly and applied as pretension elements in the model. Equivalency confirmed at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval must be computed for each QoI; E/uval < 1.96 constitutes passing.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 1.12, yield force 1.31, force at 40 mm 1.74. All three QoIs pass the pre-specified acceptance criterion. Percent differences are 3.1%, 4.2%, and 6.8% respectively, all within the 10% bound. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation must be directly linked to the failure modes and clinical risk drivers identified in the risk analysis.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness relates to load sharing with the biological tissue; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are direct surrogates for fatigue initiation and catastrophic failure risk. Linkage to FMEA risk items R-07 (screw fracture) and R-12 (rod fracture) is documented. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "A formal assessment of whether the validation activities are sufficiently relevant to the clinical context of use was considered beyond the scope of the current submission. The team noted that the F1717 test configuration is a standardized bench model and does not replicate in vivo loading spectra, patient anatomy, or bone-implant interface conditions. No structured argument mapping validation evidence to COU fidelity was produced. This factor was deferred without a compensating analysis or bounding justification, representing a material gap at modelRiskLevel 3."
    }
